--

The `java.util` date-time API and their corresponding parsing/formatting type, `SimpleDateFormat` are outdated and error-prone. In March 2014, the [modern Date-Time API](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/jf14-Date-Time.html) supplanted this API. Since then, it has been strongly recommended to switch to `java.time`, the modern date-time API.

**Solution using `java.time` API:**

You can use [`Instant#ofEpochSecond`](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/time/Instant.html#ofEpochSecond-long-) to get the `Instant` corresponding to your given Unix timestamp. Next, convert the `Instant` to a `ZonedDateTime` at the required timezone and then you can get individual time units (e.g. hour) out of this `ZonedDateTime`.

    // e.g. a Unix timestamp representing 9:00pm on 10-Sep-2023 in New York
    long epochSeconds = 1694394000L;
    Instant instant = Instant.ofEpochSecond(epochSeconds);
    ZonedDateTime zdt = instant.atZone(ZoneId.of(&quot;America/New_York&quot;));
    System.out.println(zdt);
    System.out.println(zdt.getHour());

**Output:**

    2023-09-10T21:00-04:00[America/New_York]
    21

[Online Demo](https://ideone.com/fk0BYz)

Learn more about the modern date-time API from **[Trail: Date Time](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/datetime/index.html)**

